'''Ali Asghar Khodadoust''' ({{lang-fa|علی‌اصغر خدادوست}})
(27 October 1935<ref>http://www.tourismonline.co/4747/هشتادمین-زادروز-دکتر-خدادوست.html</ref> – 10 March 2018) was an [[Iran]]ian eye surgeon specializing in [[corneal transplantation]], in whose honor the [[Khodadoust line|Khodadoust rejection line]] is named.<ref>{{cite journal| pmid=23725074 | volume=16 | issue=6 | title=The Persian legend of ophthalmology: Ali Asghar Khodadoust and his everlasting lines | year=2013 | journal=Arch Iran Med | pages=373–6 | last1 = Sajjadi | first1 = S | last2 = Fesharaki | first2 = H | last3 = Abtahi | first3 = ZA | last4 = Murray | first4 = RT | last5 = Fereidan-Esfahani | first5 = M | last6 = Mazloumi | first6 = M | last7 = Abtahi | first7 = SH}}</ref> His medical reputation was the result of his extensive studies on corneal diseases and [[organ transplantation|transplantation]] biology.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://health.usnews.com/doctors/ali-khodadoust-218909|title= Ali Asghar Khodadoust}}</ref>

==Death==
Khodadoust died at [[NewYork–Presbyterian Hospital]] in New York City on March 10, 2018. He was 82.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theiranproject.com/blog/2018/03/11/father-irans-ophthalmology-dies-82/|title=Father of Iran's ophthalmology dies at 82|website=theiranproject.com}}</ref>

